e—one that is grounded in a profound questioning of how to live a joyful, fully human life.Like Spinoza himself, the Ethics doesn’t fit into any ready-made religious category. But Carlisle shows how it wrestles with the question of religion in strikingly original ways, responding both critically and constructively to the diverse, broadly Christian context in which Spinoza lived and worked. Philosophy itself, as Spinoza practiced it, became a spiritual endeavor that expressed his devotion to a truthful, virtuous way of life. Offering startling new insights into Spinoza’s famously enigmatic ideas about eternal life and the intellectual love of God, Carlisle uncovers a Spinozist religion that integrates self-knowledge, desire, practice, and embodied ethical life to reach toward our “highest happiness”—to rest in God.Seen through Carlisle’s eyes, the Ethics prompts us to rethink not only Spinoza but also religion itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEthics, Moderny17th century. 0aPhilosophy and religionxHistoryy17th century. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAge of Enlightenment.  aAristotelianism.  aAtheism.  aBaruch Spinoza.  aCalvinism.  aCausality.  aChristian theology.  aChristian tradition.  aChristianity.  aCognition.  aConatus.  aConcept.  aConceptions of God.  aConsciousness.  aCopyright.  aCritique.  aDefinition of religion.  aDeism.  aDivine grace.  aDivine law.  aDogma.  aEpistemology.  aEssence.  aEternal life (Christianity).  aEthics (Spinoza).  aEthics.  aEx nihilo.  aExistence of God.  aExistence.  aExplanation.  aFour causes.  aGod.  aGood and evil.  aHenry Oldenburg.  aHeresy.  aHermeneutics.  aHumility.  aIdealism.  aImmanence.  aIntelligibility (philosophy).  aJudaism.